Explanation — step by step reasoning:

- I inspected controllers/user.js and identified the signup handler for POST /users/signup.
- I read the user model (models/userModel.js) and profile model (models/ProfileModel.js) to determine the properties returned in successful responses.
- The signup handler returns these HTTP responses:
  - 200 on success with a JSON body: { result, userProfile, token }
    - result is a newly created User document (fields present in the user model: name, email, password, resetToken, expireToken; Mongo _id will also be present).
    - userProfile is a ProfileModel document (fields from the profile schema) — it may be null if no profile exists, but the code includes it in the response.
    - token is a JWT string.
  - 400 for two different validation failures:
    - when a user with the email already exists -> { message: "User already exist" }
    - when password and confirmPassword do not match -> { message: "Password don't match" }
    These both use status 400 and return a JSON object with a message property.
  - 500 on unexpected errors -> { message: "Something went wrong" }.
- Based on the above, I constructed Swagger 2.0-style Response Objects for the three status codes (200, 400, 500). I included inline schema objects describing the structure of the returned JSON bodies, using only fields that appear in the models and the controller responses. I avoided using $ref and did not invent other fields.

